7.6.4 libp2p
------------

The libp2p netlayer communicates over the libp2p (https://libp2p.io)
networking stack, which is designed to provide secure peer-to-peer
connections over a variety of networking protocols.  Goblins relies upon
an external server, the Go libp2p daemon
(https://codeberg.org/spritely/go-libp2p-daemon), to access the libp2p
network.  Refer to the daemon’s documentation
(https://codeberg.org/spritely/go-libp2p-daemon) for setup instructions.

 -- Constructor: ^libp2p-netlayer [private-key] [our-location]
          [#:control-path] [#:path]

     Spawning this constructor will produce a new instance of the libp2p
     netlayer.

     The PRIVATE-KEY of type string and OUR-LOCATION of type OCapN peer
     can be used to specify an existing private key and location to be
     used by the netlayer.  If these are not specified, they are
     generated by the netlayer.  The netlayer is persistence aware so
     these do not normally need to be specified manually.

     CONTROL-PATH, when specified, is the path to the unix socket where
     the libp2p daemon is running.  If not specified it will default to
     ‘/tmp/libp2p-control.sock’

     PATH is the path to a directory where Goblins can create new
     sockets.  These sockets are used for new connections for Goblins
     and the libp2p daemon to communicate over.  It defaults to
     ‘/tmp/goblins-libp2p’

 -- Procedure: ocapn-peer->libp2p-multiaddr peer

     When provided an OCapN peer locator, it will convert this to a
     multiaddr string used by libp2p.

 -- Procedure: libp2p-multiaddress->ocapn-peer multiaddrs

     When given a string of multiaddrs, it will convert it into an OCapN
     peer locator.

 -- Persistence Environment: libp2p-netlayer-env


